'''Abra Amedomé''' was a [[Togo]]lese politician.
Trained as a [[pharmacist]] in [[France]], Amedome returned to Togo and became a highly successful businesswoman. She took a leading role in the national ruling party, and in 1975 became president of the Union National des Femmes Togolaise. In 1979 she became minister of social affairs and women's production, continuing in this role until 1983.<ref name="Sheldon2005">{{cite book|author=Kathleen E. Sheldon|title=Historical Dictionary of Women in Sub-Saharan Africa|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=36BViNOAu3sC&pg=PA1|year=2005|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=978-0-8108-5331-7|pages=1–}}</ref> She was one of six women elected to the [[Parliament of Togo]] in [[Togolese general election, 1979|1979]]; the others were [[Cheffi Meatchi]], [[Kossiwa Monsila]], [[Essohana Péré]], [[Zinabou Touré]], and [[Adjoavi Trenou]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fr.africatime.com/maroc/articles/togo-la-sous-representativite-des-femmes-au-parlement-dure-depuis-1961|title=Togo : La sous-représentativité des femmes au Parlement dure depuis 1961 !|website=fr.africatime.com|accessdate=12 September 2017}}</ref>
