[[File:Kennack Sands - geograph.org.uk - 999748.jpg|thumb|Kennack Sands]] '''Kennack Sands''' is a beach and [[Dune#Coastal dunes|sand-dune]] system on the east coast of the [[Lizard Peninsula]], [[Cornwall]], England, [[United Kingdom|UK]].<ref>{{cite book|title=Explorer Map 103. The Lizard|date=2010|publisher=Ordnance Survey|location=Southampton|isbn=978-0-319-24117-2|edition=A2}}</ref>
==Geography== The beach is approximately {{convert|500|m|ft}} long and backed by cliffs, Kennack Towans (sand-dune system) and [[Tor (rock formation)|Carn]] Kennack. Inland is the abandoned Gwendreath Quarry. The beach is used for recreation and divided into two by an outcrop of rocks called the Caerverracks. Kennack Sands has a gentle sloping beach so the tidal range is quite large. At high tide there is still a large amount of beach to make use of but at low tide the beach seems to get a lot bigger. There is a rocky outcrop that splits the beach into two so the beach may be referred to as Kennack Sands west and Kennack Sands East. The rock that splits the beaches is called Caerverracks and the hill above this Carn Kennack. There is a path that runs over Carn Kennack allowing access to the east beach which is a designated nature reserve.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gocornwallbeaches.com/destination/the-lizard-falmouth-and-helston/kennack-sands-beach/|title=Kennack Sands Beach - Go Cornwall Beaches|language=en-US|access-date=2016-09-07}}</ref>
It is a popular site for launching [[Inflatable boat|inflatables]] for [[underwater diving]]. Less than {{convert|400|m|ft}} off-shore the depth of water is over {{convert|16|m|ft}}.<ref name="dsc">{{cite book|last1=Larn|first1=Richard|title=Dive South Cornwall|date=1996|publisher=Underwater World Productions|location=Teddington, Middlesex|isbn=0 946020 25 6|edition=3rd}}</ref>
The nearest village is [[Kuggar]], {{convert|1|km|mile}} inland. There is a car park and café on the western side of the beach and on the road to Kuggar there are caravan and camping sites.
==History== Pill boxes and an anti-tank wall were built on the back of the beach in case of invasion during the [[World War II|Second World War]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Monument No. 1419309 |url=http://www.pastscape.org/hob.aspx?hob_id=1419309&sort=2&type=&rational=a&class1=None&period=None&county=1306805&district=None&parish=None&place=GRADE%20RUAN&recordsperpage=10&source=text&rtype=&rnumber=&p=9&move=n&nor=154&recfc=0 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222093858/http://www.pastscape.org/hob.aspx?hob_id=1419309&sort=2&type=&rational=a&class1=None&period=None&county=1306805&district=None&parish=None&place=GRADE%20RUAN&recordsperpage=10&source=text&rtype=&rnumber=&p=9&move=n&nor=154&recfc=0 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=22 December 2015 |website=Pastscape |publisher=Historic England |accessdate=20 December 2015 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Monument No. 1419311 |url=http://www.pastscape.org/hob.aspx?hob_id=1419311&sort=2&type=&rational=a&class1=None&period=None&county=1306805&district=None&parish=None&place=GRADE%20RUAN&recordsperpage=10&source=text&rtype=&rnumber=&p=9&move=n&nor=154&recfc=0 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222104316/http://www.pastscape.org/hob.aspx?hob_id=1419311&sort=2&type=&rational=a&class1=None&period=None&county=1306805&district=None&parish=None&place=GRADE%20RUAN&recordsperpage=10&source=text&rtype=&rnumber=&p=9&move=n&nor=154&recfc=0 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=22 December 2015 |website=Pastscape |publisher=Historic England |accessdate=20 December 2015 }}</ref>
